The two sides formalized a Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) on 22 February 2002, and signed a permanent cease-fire agreement (CFA). Norway was named [[mediation|mediator]], and it was decided that they, together with the other Nordic countries, monitor the cease-fire through a committee of experts named the [[Sri Lanka Monitoring Mission]].<ref name="bbc3">{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/1835737.stm|title =Sri Lanka seals truce deal|publisher=BBC News |date= 22 February 2002 |accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref> In August the government agreed to lift the ban on the LTTE and paved the way for the resumption of direct negotiations with them.<ref name="bbc4">{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/2217189.stm|title =Colombo lifts ban on Tamil Tigers|publisher=BBC News|date = 26 August 2002|accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref>
[[File:Sea Tiger Fast Attack boat.jpg|thumb|left|LTTE Sea Tiger boat patrolling during the peace]]

Following the signing of the ceasefire agreement, commercial air flights to Jaffna began and the LTTE opened the key A9 highway, which linked the government-controlled area in the south with Jaffna and ran through LTTE territory, allowing civilian traffic through the Vanni region for the first time in many years (but only after paying a tax to the LTTE). Many foreign countries also offered substantial financial support if peace was achieved and optimism grew that an end to the decades-long conflict was in sight.

The much-anticipated peace talks began in [[Phuket Province|Phuket]], Thailand, and further rounds followed in Thailand, Norway, Germany and Japan.<ref name="bbc5">{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/2260047.stm|title=Upbeat opening for Sri Lanka talks |publisher=BBC News | date=16 September 2002 | accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref> During the talks both sides agreed to the principle of a federal solution and the Tigers dropped their long-standing demand for a separate state. This was a major compromise on the part of the LTTE, which had always insisted on an independent Tamil state. This also represented a compromise on the part of the government, which had seldom agreed to more than minimal devolution. Both sides also exchanged prisoners of war for the first time.<ref name="autogenerated2">''BBC News'', " [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/country_profiles/1166237.stm Timeline: Sri Lanka]".</ref>

===Political changes in the South===
Following the elections of 2001, for the first time in Sri Lanka's history the President and Prime Minister were of two different parties. This co-habitation was uneasy, especially since Prime Minister Wickremasinghe and the UNP favored a federal solution to the conflict, while hard-line elements within President Kumaratunga's party and other Sinhala nationalist groups allied to her opposed one, as they did not trust the LTTE, which continued to levy taxes, strengthen itself by smuggling in arms and ammunition, recruit child soldiers and engage in killings of members of rival Tamil groups and government intelligence agents following the [[Millennium City incident]]. During this time the LTTE also succeeded in setting up a series of vital bases around the [[Trincomalee Harbour]] (''i.e.'', Manirasakulam camp) and the Eastern Province.

The talks broke down on 21 April 2003 when the Tamil Tigers announced they were suspending any further talks due to their "displeasure" at the handling of some "critical issues". Among the reasons the Tigers gave were their exclusion from reconstruction talks in Washington, DC, on 14 April and a more general insinuation that they were not receiving the full economic rewards of peace. They cited the failure, as they saw it, of peace dividends to transfer to security withdrawals on the ground and the disparity, as they saw it, between the relative calm of the government-held northeast and continuing violence in Tiger-held areas. However, the LTTE maintained it was committed to a settlement to the two-decade conflict, but stated that progress had to be made on the ground before the settlement proceeded.<ref name="bbc6">{{cite news|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/2964349.stm|title =Tamil Tigers call off peace talks|publisher=BBC News|date = 21 April 2003|accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref>

On 31 October the LTTE issued its own peace proposal, calling for an ''[[Interim Self Governing Authority]]'' (ISGA). The ISGA would be fully controlled by the LTTE and would have broad powers in the north and east (see the [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/3232913.stm full text of the proposals]) This provoked a strong backlash among the hard-line elements in the south, who accused Prime Minister Wickremasinghe of handing the north and east to the LTTE. Under pressure from within her own party to take action, Kumaratunga declared a state of emergency and took three key government ministries, the Ministry of Mass Media, the Interior Ministry and the crucial Defense Ministry.<ref name="bbc7">{{cite news|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/3239303.stm|title =Sri Lanka thrown into political crisis|publisher=BBC News|date = 4 November 2003|accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref> She then formed an alliance with the JVP, called the [[United People's Freedom Alliance]], opposed to the ISGA and advocating a harder line on the LTTE, and called for fresh elections. The [[Sri Lankan parliamentary election, 2004|elections]], held on 8 April 2004, resulted in victory for the [[United People's Freedom Alliance|UPFA]] with [[Mahinda Rajapakse]] appointed as Prime Minister.

===Split of the LTTE===
Meanwhile, in March 2004 there had been a major split between the northern and eastern wings of the LTTE. [[Vinayagamoorthy Muralitharan]] ''alias'' Col. Karuna, the Eastern commander of the LTTE and one of Prabhakaran's trusted lieutenants, pulled 5,000 eastern cadres out of the LTTE, claiming insufficient resources and power were being given to Tamils of the eastern part of the island. It was the biggest expression of dissension in the history of the LTTE and a clash within the LTTE seemed imminent. After the parliamentary elections, brief fighting south of Trincomalee led to a rapid retreat and capitulation of Karuna's group, their leaders eventually going into hiding including Karuna himself, who was helped to escape by [[Seyed Ali Zahir Moulana]], a politician from the ruling party. However, the "Karuna faction" maintained a significant presence in the east and continued to launch attacks against the LTTE.<ref name="nyt2">{{cite news|url =https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/31/world/asia/31lanka.html?_r=1&oref=slogin|title =Sri Lanka Says Rebels Took Losses in Raids|work=The New York Times|date = 31 December 2006}}</ref> The LTTE accused the army of covertly backing the breakaway group, which subsequently formed a political party named the [[TamilEela Makkal Viduthalai Pulikal]] (TMVP) and hope to contest in future elections.

The cease-fire largely held through all this turmoil, with over 3000 infractions by the LTTE and some 300 by the SLA recorded by the Sri Lanka Monitoring Mission (SLMM) by 2005.<ref>Sri Lanka peace secretariat report, 2005.</ref> The situation was further complicated by allegations that both sides were carrying out covert operations against each other. The government claimed that the LTTE was killing political opponents, recruiting children, importing arms and killing government security and intelligence officers. The rebels accused the government of supporting paramilitary groups against them, especially the Karuna group.

===Tsunami and aftermath===
On 26 December 2004, the [[Indian Ocean tsunami]] struck Sri Lanka, killing more than 35,000 people and leaving many more homeless. A great deal of aid arrived from around the world, but there was immediate disagreement over how it should be distributed to the Tamil regions under LTTE control. By 24 June the government and LTTE agreed on the Post-Tsunami Operational Management Structure (P-TOMS), but it received sharp criticism from the [[Janatha Vimukthi Peramuna|JVP]], who left the government in protest. The legality of P-TOMS was also challenged in the courts. President Kumaratunga eventually had to scrap P-TOMS, which led to widespread criticism that sufficient aid was not reaching the north and east of the country. However, immediately following the tsunami there was a marked decrease in violence in the north.{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}

Sri Lankan Foreign Minister [[Lakshman Kadirgamar]], a Tamil who was highly respected by foreign diplomats and who had been sharply critical of the LTTE, was assassinated at his home on 12 August 2005, allegedly by an LTTE sniper.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4147196.stm | title=Senior Sri Lanka minister killed | accessdate=13 August 2005 |publisher=BBC News | date=13 August 2005}}</ref> His assassination led to the marginalization of the LTTE from the international community, and is generally considered to be the moment when the LTTE lost much of its sympathy in the eyes of foreign nations. Hence the silence of the international community when the Sri Lankan government took military action against the LTTE in 2006, when the latter closed the Mavil aru sluice.{{elucidate|date=July 2012}}

Further political change occurred when the [[Supreme Court of Sri Lanka]] declared President Kumaratunga's second and final term over and ordered her to hold fresh presidential elections. The main candidates for the [[Sri Lankan presidential election, 2005|election]], which was held in November, were UNF candidate former Prime Minister Ranil Wickremasinghe, who advocated the reopening of talks with the LTTE, and the UPFA candidate Prime Minister Rajapaksa, who called for a tougher line against the LTTE and a renegotiation of the cease-fire. The LTTE openly called for a [[boycott]] of the election by Tamils. Many of them were expected to vote for Wickremasinghe, and the loss of their votes proved fatal to his chances, as Rajapakse achieved a narrow victory. Following the election, LTTE leader [[Velupillai Prabhakaran]] stated in his annual address that the Tigers would "renew their struggle" in 2006 if the government did not take serious moves toward peace.

==Resumption of hostilities==
[[File:Extent of territorial control in sri lanka.png|thumb|Red area shows the approximate areas of Sri Lanka controlled by the LTTE and the Government, as of December 2005.]]
{{Main article|Eelam War IV}}
Beginning in December 2005, there was increased guerrilla activity to the northeast, including [[M18A1 Claymore Antipersonnel Mine|Claymore mine]] attacks which killed 150 government troops,<ref name="st1">{{cite news|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/060430/index.html|title=How President decided on retaliation|work=The Sunday Times |date=30 April 2006}}</ref> clashes between the [[Sea Tigers]] and the Sri Lanka navy and the killings of sympathizers on both sides including [[Taraki Sivaram]], a pro-LTTE journalist, and [[Joseph Pararajasingham]], a pro-LTTE MP, both killed allegedly by the government of Sri Lanka.

At the beginning of 2006 the focus of the civil war turned to civilian targets, with commuter bus and train bombings carried out in most parts of the country, including a series of attacks against commuters in and around Colombo.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7440183.stm|title=Sri Lanka's war turns on civilians|publisher=BBC News|date=6 June 2008|accessdate=4 January 2010|first=Frances|last=Harrison}}</ref>

===Talks and further violence===
In light of this violence, the co-chairs of the Tokyo Donor conference called on both parties to return to the negotiating table. [[US State Department]] officials gave warnings to the Tigers, stating that a return to hostilities would mean that the Tigers would face a "more capable and more determined" Sri Lankan military.<ref name="ind1">{{cite news|url=http://news.independent.co.uk/world/asia/article338232.ece |title=Sri Lanka bomb attack fuels fear of return to civil war |work=The Independent |date=13 January 2006 |location=London |first=Justin |last=Huggler |accessdate=9 April 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080110153720/http://news.independent.co.uk/world/asia/article338232.ece |archivedate=10 January 2008 }}</ref> While the talks were going on there was violence directed towards civilians, such as [[2006 Trincomalee massacre|the killings of five Tamil students]] on 2 January 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nation.lk/2006/07/23/newsfe3.htm|title=Is the State complacent?|accessdate=30 January 2007 |work=The Nation |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930224026/http://www.nation.lk/2006/07/23/newsfe3.htm |archivedate = 30 September 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ahrchk.net/statements/mainfile.php/2006statements/612/|title='Murder of five Tamil youths highlights need to end impunity' – Govt must protect witnesses to Trinco killings – Human Rights Watch|accessdate=30 January 2007 |publisher=Human Rights Watch}}</ref>

In a last-minute effort to salvage an agreement between the parties, Norwegian special envoy [[Erik Solheim]] and LTTE theoretician Anton Balasingham arrived on the island. The parties strongly disagreed on the location of the talks; however, continued efforts produced a breakthrough when both parties agreed on 7 February 2006 that new talks could be held in [[Geneva]], Switzerland, on 22 and 23 February. During the weeks after the talks there was a significant decrease in violence. However, the LTTE resumed attacks against the military in April.

In light of this violence, the LTTE called for a postponement of the Geneva talks until 24–25 April, and the government initially agreed to this. Following negotiations, both the government and the rebels agreed to have a civilian vessel transport regional LTTE leaders with international truce monitors on 16 April, which involved crossing government-controlled territory. However, the climate shifted drastically when the Tigers cancelled the meeting, claiming not to have agreed to a naval escort. According to the SLMM, the Tamil rebels had previously agreed to the escort.<ref name="bbc8">{{cite news|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/4911554.stm|title = Tamil Tigers harden talks stance|publisher=BBC News| date = 17 April 2006|accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref>

On 20 April 2006 the LTTE officially pulled out of peace talks indefinitely. While they stated that transportation issues had prevented them from meeting their regional leaders, some analysts and the international community were strongly skeptical, seeing the transportation issue as a delaying tactic by the LTTE to avoid attending peace talks in Geneva.<ref name="bbc9">{{cite news|url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/sinhala/news/story/2006/04/printable/060423_eu_ban.shtml|title = EU ban on LTTE urged|publisher=BBC News|date = 23 April 2006}}</ref> Violence continued to spiral and on 23 April 2006, [[Gomarankadawala massacre|six Sinhalese rice farmers were massacred]] in their paddy fields by suspected LTTE cadres,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2006/04/30/fea13.html|title=LTTE carnage at Gomarankadawala:Its significance|publisher=Sunday Obsrver|date=30 April 2006|accessdate=21 January 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130905181758/http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2006/04/30/fea13.html|archivedate=5 September 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and on 13 May 2006 [[Allaipiddy massacre|13 Tamil civilians were killed]] in the [[List of islands of Sri Lanka#Northern Province|islet of Kayts]].<ref>{{cite news|first = Dumeetha|last = Luthra|title = Sri Lanka villagers flee massacre|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5000920.stm|publisher=BBC|date=20 May 2006|accessdate=16 August 2007}}</ref> International condemnation against the LTTE skyrocketed following the attempted assassination of the commander of the Sri Lanka Army, Lt. Gen. [[Sarath Fonseka]], by a female LTTE [[Black Tigers|Black Tiger]] [[suicide bomber]] named Anoja Kugenthirasah, who concealed the explosives by appearing to be pregnant and blew herself up at army headquarters in [[Colombo]]. For the first time since the 2001 cease-fire, the Sri Lanka Air Force carried out aerial assaults on rebel positions in the northeastern part of the island in retaliation for the attack.<ref>{{cite news |url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4941744.stm |title=Bomb targets Sri Lanka army chief|publisher=BBC News|date=25 April 2006|accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref>

This attack, along with the assassination of Lakshman Kadiragamar a year earlier and an unsuccessful attack against a naval vessel carrying 710 unarmed security force personnel on holiday, marked a turning point, as the [[European Union]] decided to proscribe the LTTE as a terrorist organisation on 19 May 2006. It resulted in the freezing of LTTE assets in its 27 member nations. In a statement, the [[European Parliament]] said that the LTTE did not represent all the Tamils and called on it to "allow for political pluralism and alternate democratic voices in the northern and eastern parts of Sri Lanka".<ref name="hindu1">{{cite news|url =http://www.hindu.com/2006/05/31/stories/2006053117200100.htm| title=European Union bans LTTE| work=Amit Baruah|date = 31 May 2006|location=Chennai, India}}</ref> As the north and east of the country continued to be rocked by attacks, new talks were scheduled in Oslo, Norway, between 8–9 June. Delegations from both sides arrived in Oslo, but the talks were cancelled when the LTTE refused to meet directly with the government delegation, claiming its fighters were not allowed safe passage to travel to the talks. Norwegian mediator Erik Solheim told journalists that the LTTE should take direct responsibility for the collapse of the talks.<ref name="bbc10">{{cite news|url =http://www.bbc.co.uk/sinhala/news/story/2006/06/060609_saroj-oslo.shtml|title=Collapse of talks|work =Saroj Pathirana|publisher=BBC News|date = 9 June 2006}}</ref>

Further violence followed, including the [[Vankalai massacre]]. The Sri Lankan army and [[Tamil Tiger]] rebels blamed each other for the killings.<ref name="AN">{{cite web| url = http://www.asianews.it/index.php?l=en&art=6425|title = People terrorized after massacre of Tamil family| publisher =AsiaSat News|date =13 June 2006|accessdate=22 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/rds/pdfs06/sri_lanka_021106.doc |title=Country of origin information report– Sri Lanka |accessdate=22 January 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325153828/http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/rds/pdfs06/sri_lanka_021106.doc |archivedate=25 March 2009 }}</ref> There was also the [[Kebithigollewa massacre]] in which the LTTE attacked a bus, killing at least 64 Sinhalese civilians and prompting more air strikes by the Air Force,<ref name="usinfo1">''United States International Information Programs''", [http://www.america.gov/st/washfile-english/2006/June/20060615115032ndyblehs0.351742.html United States Condemns Terrorist Attack on Sri Lankan Bus]. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090202201603/http://www.america.gov/st/washfile-english/2006/June/20060615115032ndyblehs0.351742.html |date=2 February 2009 }}</ref> and the assassination of Sri Lanka's third highest-ranking army officer and Deputy Chief of Staff [[Parami Kulatunga|General Parami Kulatunga]] on 26 June by an LTTE suicide bomber.<ref name="bbc11">{{cite news|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5115968.stm| title=Sri Lanka general killed in blast|publisher=BBC News|date = 26 June 2006|accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref> These events led the [[Sri Lanka Monitoring Mission|SLMM]] to question whether a cease-fire could still be said to exist.<ref name="slmm1">{{cite web|url=http://www.slmm.lk/intros/press_releases.htm|title=Press releases|accessdate=7 August 2006|publisher=Sri Lanka Monitoring Mission|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070312223248/http://www.slmm.lk/intros/press_releases.htm|archivedate=12 March 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

===Mavil Aru water dispute===
A new crisis leading to the first large-scale fighting since signing of the cease-fire occurred when the LTTE closed the [[sluice gate]]s of the [[Mavil Aru]] reservoir on 21 July. Mavil Aru was the waterway that provided water to some regions of eastern Sri Lanka, like [[Trincomalee]]. After the cease-fire in 2002, the conflict over Mavil Aru was one of the biggest military confrontations between the [[Sri Lanka Armed Forces]] and the LTTE. Its relevance is for geo-strategic reasons: within the Mavil Aru area, Sinhala, Muslim and Tamil populations live side by side. It is also the entrance to Koddiyar Bay, the inlet for Trincomalee port and naval base, so the LTTE presence in the area seriously threatened the Sri Lankan security forices' presence and domination.

Closure of Mavil Aru affected the water supply to 15,000 families in government-controlled areas.<ref name="bbc12">{{cite news|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5249884.stm|title = Sri Lanka forces attack reservoir|publisher=BBC News|date=6 August 2006|accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref> After the initial negotiations and efforts by the SLMM to open the gates failed, the Sri Lanka military initiated an operation to achieve the re-opening of the sluice gates.

President Rajapaksa said that the supply of water was a non-negotiable fundamental human right. Additionally, a government spokesman said that "''utilities could not be used as bargaining tools''" by the rebels.<ref name="bbc12" /> The government deployed its army and air force for the offensive, attacking not only the region of [[Mavil Aru]] but also the LTTE positions in [[Batticaloa]], and [[Vavuniya]]. Air Force planes attacked LTTE positions on 26 July, and ground troops began an operation to open the gate.<ref name="south"/> The sluice gates were eventually reopened on 8 August, with conflicting reports as to who actually opened them. Initially, the SLMM claimed that they managed to persuade the LTTE to lift the waterway blockade conditionally.<ref name="nation.lk"/> The LTTE claimed that it opened the sluice gates "on humanitarian grounds", although this was disputed by military correspondents, who stated the water began flowing immediately after security forces carried out a precise bombing of the Mavil Aru anicut.<ref name="st2">''The Sunday Times Situation Report'', [http://sundaytimes.lk/060813/index.html Eelam war IV rages on several fronts].</ref> Eventually, following heavy fighting, government troops gained full control of the Mavil Aru reservoir on 15 August.<ref name="nation.lk">{{cite news | url=http://www.nation.lk/2009/05/19/news19.html | title=Operation Liberation | work=[[The Nation (Sri Lanka)|The Nation]] | date=19 May 2009 | accessdate=29 April 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100330213340/http://www.nation.lk/2009/05/19/news19.html | archive-date=30 March 2010 | dead-url=yes | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The consequences of the "Operation Watershed" were about 150 civilians killed and more than 50,000 refugees from [[Mutur]] and the villages nearby. It was the precedent of the [[Eelam War IV]].<ref name="south">{{cite news|url=http://www.southasiaanalysis.org/%5Cpapers20%5Cpaper1908.html |title=Sri Lanka: Mavil Aru Operation and After – An Analysis |publisher=southasiaanalysis.org |date=12 August 2006 |accessdate=4 March 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620203142/http://southasiaanalysis.org/papers20/paper1908.html |archivedate=20 June 2010 }}</ref>

===LTTE offensives in Muttur and Jaffna===
As fierce fighting was ongoing in the vicinity of Mavil Aru, violence spread to Trincomalee, where the LTTE launched an attack on a crucial Sri Lanka Navy base,<ref name="south2">{{cite news|url=http://www.southasiaanalysis.org/%5Cnotes4%5Cnote325.html |title=LTTE strikes back – Update No. 98 |publisher=southasiaanalysis.org |date=15 August 2006 |accessdate=29 April 2012 |author=Hariharan, R. |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101128160927/http://southasiaanalysis.org/notes4/note325.html |archivedate=28 November 2010 }}</ref> and to the strategic government-controlled coastal town of Muttur in early August, resulting in the deaths of at least 30 civilians and displacing 25,000 residents of the area.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5240864.stm |title = Civilians die in Sri Lanka clash |publisher=BBC News |date = 3 August 2006|accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref> The clashes erupted on 2 August 2006 when the LTTE launched a heavy artillery attack on Muttur<ref name="toi1">{{cite news |url =http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/1859354.cms |title = 152 LTTE rebels killed in Sri Lanka |work=The Times of India  |date = 4 August 2006}}</ref> and then moved in, gaining control of some parts of the town.<ref name="hindu2">{{cite news |url =http://www.hindu.com/2006/08/04/stories/2006080408511500.htm |title=34 killed as LTTE `overruns' Muttur town |work=B. Muralidhar Reddy | date=4 August 2006 | location=Chennai, India}}</ref> The military retaliated, and re-established full control over the town by 5 August, killing over 150 LTTE fighters in heavy clashes.<ref name="toi1" />

Soon afterwards, 17 persons working for the International French charity [[Action Against Hunger]] (ACF) in Muthur, [[2006 Trincomalee massacre of NGO workers|were massacred]]. They were found lying face down on the floor of their office, shot to death, still wearing their clearly marked T-shirts indicating they were international humanitarian workers. The murders prompted widespread international condemnation.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.hindu.com/2006/08/08/stories/2006080808521200.htm |title=15 NGO workers killed |accessdate=30 January 2007 |work=The Hindu  |location=Chennai, India |date=8 August 2006}}</ref> The SLMM claimed that the government was behind the attack,<ref>{{cite news |url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5298470.stm |title = Military 'killed Lanka aid staff' |publisher=BBC |date = 30 August 2006|accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref> but the government denied the allegation calling it "pathetic and biased", and stated that the SLMM had "no right to make such a statement because they are not professionals in autopsy or post-mortem."<ref>{{cite news|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5298470.stm|title = Sri Lanka forces attack reservoir|publisher=BBC News|date=6 August 2006|accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref>

Meanwhile, in the north of the country, some of the bloodiest fighting since 2001 took place after the LTTE launched massive attacks on [[Sri Lanka Army]] defense lines on the Jaffna peninsula on 11 August. The LTTE used a force of 400–500 fighters in the attacks, which consisted of land and amphibious assaults, and also fired a barrage of artillery at government positions, including the key military airbase at [[Palaly Military Base|Palaly]].<ref name="south2" /><ref name="oi1">{{cite news|url = http://news.oneindia.in/2006/08/12/sri-lanka-rebels-say-destroy-northern-defences-advance-1155353635.html|title = Lanka rebels destroy northern defenses, advance |publisher = One India| date = 12 August 2006}}</ref> The LTTE is estimated to have lost over 200 fighters in the operation, while 90 Sri Lankan soldiers and sailors were also killed.<ref name="usatoday1">{{cite news|url = https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2006-08-15-sri-lanka_x.htm|title = Fighting rages in northern Sri Lanka in fourth week of hostilities |work=USA Today| date = 15 August 2006}}</ref>

As ground battles were ongoing in the north and the east of the country, the Sri Lanka Air Force carried out an air strike against a facility in the rebel-held Mullaitivu area, [[Chencholai airstrike|killing a number of Tamil girls]]. Although the LTTE claimed 61 girls were killed, the SLMM stated they were able to count just 19 bodies.<ref name="hind">{{cite news | url=http://www.hindu.com/2006/08/15/stories/2006081512460100.htm | title=Suicide attack in Colombo |work=The Hindu  | date=15 August 2006 | accessdate=29 April 2012 | author=Reddy, B. Muralidhar}}</ref> The government stated that it was an LTTE training facility and that the children were LTTE child soldiers,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.unicef.org/media/media_35336.html | title=UNICEF: Children are victims of the conflict in Sri Lanka | publisher=[[UNICEF]] | date=15 August 2006 | accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref> although the LTTE claimed the victims were schoolgirls attending a course on first aid at an orphanage.

On the same day a convoy carrying the Pakistani [[High Commissioner]] to Sri Lanka, Bashir Wali Mohamed, was [[Attack on Pakistani ambassador to Sri lanka|attacked]] when a [[M18A1 Claymore Antipersonnel Mine|claymore antipersonnel mine]] concealed within an [[auto rickshaw]] blew up as it passed by. The High Commissioner escaped unhurt, but seven people were killed and 17 injured in the blast.<ref name="bbc4789991">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4789991.stm | title=Seven killed in Colombo explosion |publisher=BBC | date=14 August 2006 | accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref> The High Commissioner claimed that India was believed to have carried it out,<ref name="at2">{{cite web|url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/South_Asia/HI22Df01.html|title=The Pakistani muscle behind Colombo|author = Sudha Ramachandran|date= 22 September 2006|work =Asia Times}}</ref> in order to intimidate Pakistan, which is one of the main suppliers of military equipment to the Sri Lankan government.<ref name="at2" /> Pakistan had promised one shipload of equipment every 10 days in coming months.

===Fall of Sampur===
Since the resumption of violence, concerns were mounting among the military establishment that the strategically crucial<ref name="reuters1">{{cite news|url = http://today.reuters.co.uk/news/CrisesArticle.aspx?storyId=COL24804|title = Sri Lanka army battles rebels in northeast|work = Peter Apps|agency = Reuters|date = 12 September 2006|deadurl = yes|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060903184404/http://today.reuters.co.uk/News/CrisesArticle.aspx?storyId=COL24804|archivedate = 3 September 2006|df = dmy-all}}</ref> Sri Lanka Navy base in Trincomalee was under severe threat from LTTE gun positions located in and around Sampur, which lies across the Koddiyar Bay from Trincomalee.<ref name="hindu4">{{cite news |url = http://www.hindu.com/2006/09/05/stories/2006090505251300.htm|title = Sri Lankan army captures Sampur|work = The Hindu |date = 5 September 2006 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref> Artillery fired from LTTE bases in the area could potentially cripple the naval base, bringing it to a complete standstill and cutting the only military supply chain to Jaffna. All movements of naval vessels were also under the constant surveillance of the LTTE.<ref name="south3">{{cite web|url=http://www.southasiaanalysis.org/%5Cnotes4%5Cnote331.html |title=Sri Lanka: LTTE's moment of truth at Sampur – Update 101 |publisher=southasiaanalysis.org |date=8 September 2006 |accessdate=29 April 2012 |author=Hariharan, R. |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101128074835/http://southasiaanalysis.org/notes4/note331.html |archivedate=28 November 2010 }}</ref> These fears were backed up by a US military advisory team which visited the island in 2005.

Following clashes in Mavil Aru and Muttur, the LTTE had intensified attacks targeting the naval base in Trincomalee,<ref name="hindu4" /> and in a speech on 21 August Sri Lankan president Mahinda Rajapakse made clear the government intentions were to neutralize the LTTE threat from Sampur.<ref name="hindu4" /> On 28 August the military launched an assault to retake the LTTE camps in Sampur and the adjoining Kaddaiparichchan and Thoppur areas. This led the LTTE to declare that if the offensive continued, the cease-fire would be officially over.

After steady progress, security forces led by Brigade Commander Sarath Wijesinghe<ref name="hindu5" /> recaptured Sampur from the LTTE on 4 September and began to establish military bases there,<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601080&sid=ax6hzULkWuCE|title = Sri Lanka Army captures Sampur|publisher = Bloomberg|date = 4 September 2006|deadurl = yes|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930045935/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601080&sid=ax6hzULkWuCE|archivedate = 30 September 2007|df = dmy-all}}</ref> as the LTTE admitted defeat and stated their fighters "withdrew" from the strategically important town.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/sinhala/news/story/2006/09/060904_sampoor_defeat.shtml| title = LTTE admits defeat in Sampoor|publisher=BBC |date = 4 September 2006}}</ref> It marked the first significant territorial change of hands since the signing of the cease-fire agreement in 2002.<ref name="iht1">{{cite news|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2006/09/04/asia/AS_GEN_Sri_Lanka.php |title=Sri Lankan military captures key rebel territory, Tigers vow to keep fighting |work=International Herald Tribune |date=3 September 2006 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080629120955/http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2006/09/04/asia/AS_GEN_Sri_Lanka.php |archivedate=29 June 2008 }}</ref> The Sri Lankan military estimated that 33 of its personnel were killed in the offensive, along with over 200 LTTE fighters.<ref name="hindu5">{{cite news |url = http://www.hindu.com/2006/09/12/stories/2006091204601400.htm|title = Fierce battles continue in Jaffna|work = The Hindu|date = 12 September 2006|location=Chennai, India}}</ref>

===LTTE retaliation and further peace talks===
The LTTE struck back in October. First, they killed nearly 130 soldiers in a fierce battle at Muhamalai, the crossing-point between government- and LTTE-controlled area in the north of the country.<ref name="sunday1">{{cite news | url=http://sundaytimes.lk/061015/Columns/sitreport.html | title=Muhamalai debacle: The shocking story | work=[[The Sunday Times (Sri Lanka)|The Sunday Times]] | date=15 October 2006 | accessdate=29 April 2012 | author=[[Iqbal Athas|Athas, Iqbal]]}}</ref> Just days later, a suspected LTTE suicide bomber [[2006 Digampathana bombing|struck a naval convoy]] in Habarana, in the center of the country, killing about 100 sailors who were returning home on leave.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/6045866.stm| title = Analysis: Sri Lanka military setbacks|publisher=BBC |date = 16 October 2006|accessdate=4 January 2010|first=Dumeetha|last=Luthra}}</ref> It was the deadliest suicide attack in the history of the conflict.<ref name="zaman1">{{cite news|url = http://www.zaman.com/?bl=international&alt=&hn=37451|title = Bloody Day in Sri Lanka: 103 Dead|work = Zaman Daily|date = 17 October 2006|deadurl = yes|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110511061254/http://www.zaman.com/?bl=international&alt=&hn=37451|archivedate = 11 May 2011|df = dmy-all}}</ref>

Two days later LTTE Sea Tiger forces launched an attack against the ''Dakshina'' naval base in the southern port city of [[Galle]]. It was the farthest south any major LTTE attack had taken place, and involved 15 LTTE fighters who arrived in five suicide boats. The attack was repulsed by the government, and the damage to the naval base was minimal. All 15 LTTE fighters were believed to have died in the attack, along with one Navy sailor.<ref name="hindu6">{{cite news|url = http://www.hindu.com/2006/10/19/stories/2006101915420100.htm|title = LTTE attack on Galle repulsed |work =The Hindu |date=19 October 2006|location=Chennai, India}}</ref>

Despite these incidents, both parties agreed to unconditionally attend peace talks in Geneva on 28–29 October.<ref name="south4">{{cite web|url=http://www.southasiaanalysis.org/%5Cnotes4%5Cnote339.html |title=Sri Lanka: Contradictions of a military agenda – Update 104 |publisher=southasiaanalysis.org |date=10 October 2006 |accessdate=29 April 2012 |author=Hariharan, R. |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101128162842/http://southasiaanalysis.org/notes4/note339.html |archivedate=28 November 2010 }}</ref> However, the peace talks broke down due to disagreements over the reopening of the key A9 highway, which is the link between Jaffna and government-controlled areas in the south. While the LTTE wanted the highway, which was closed following fierce battles in August, to be reopened, the government refused, stating the LTTE would use it to collect taxes from people passing through and would use it to launch further offensives against government troops.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2006/10/29/europe/EU_GEN_Switzerland_Sri_Lanka_Talks.php |title=Sri Lankan peace talks end in deadlock over road blockade |work=International Herald tribune |date=28 October 2006 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090321013934/http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2006/10/29/europe/EU_GEN_Switzerland_Sri_Lanka_Talks.php |archivedate=21 March 2009 }}</ref>

Following the dawn of the new year, suspected [[LTTE]] fighters carried out two bus bombings in the south of the country, killing 21 civilians. News reports stated that the attacks bore all the hallmarks of an LTTE attack.<ref name="an1">{{cite news|url =http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/COL157334.htm| title =Fear and loathing in south Sri Lanka after bus bombs| work =Buddhika Weerasinghe|agency = Reuters|date = 8 January 2007}}</ref> The Sri Lankan government condemned the attacks and blamed the LTTE for carrying them out, although the LTTE denied any involvement.<ref name="mcns1">''Media Center for National Security'', [http://www.nationalsecurity.lk/fullnews.php?id=3298 The Government Condemns LTTE Terror Attacks on Civilians] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070223055805/http://www.nationalsecurity.lk/fullnews.php?id=3298 |date=23 February 2007 }}.</ref>

===Government offensive in the East===
{{Main article|Eastern Theater of Eelam War IV}}
{{See also|Operation Definite Victory}}
In December 2006 Sri Lankan government officials announced their plans to drive the LTTE out of the [[Eastern Province, Sri Lanka|Eastern Province]] of Sri Lanka, and then use the full strength of the military to defeat the LTTE in the north of the country. The government stated that LTTE was firing artillery towards civilian settlements in the east and were using 35,000 people as human shields.<ref name="reuters-14 December 2006">{{cite news|url = http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/COL298949.htm|title =Sri Lanka military vows to drive Tigers from east coast| agency = Reuters|date = 14 December 2006}}</ref> These claims were later backed up by civilians in the area, who told reporters that they were held by force by the Tamil Tigers.<ref name="iht-18 December 2006">{{cite news|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2006/12/18/asia/AS_GEN_Sri_Lanka_Refugees.php |title=Fleeing Tamil refugees describe being held by separatists as Sri Lanka shelled camps |work=International Herald Tribune |date=18 December 2006 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080205184839/http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2006/12/18/asia/AS_GEN_Sri_Lanka_Refugees.php |archivedate=5 February 2008 }}</ref> On 7 November 2006, amidst conflicting claims, over 45 Tamil civilians were killed in what is known as the [[Vaharai bombing]].

Subsequently, the army began an offensive against the LTTE on 8 December 2006, in the Batticoloa district with the objective of taking [[Vakarai (Sri Lanka)|Vakarai]], the principal stronghold of the LTTE in the east; the operation was temporarily aborted after a week of fighting due to the large number of civilians in the area and the difficulty in conducting combat operations due to the ongoing [[monsoon]] rain.<ref name="uthr1">{{cite web | url=http://www.uthr.org/bulletins/Bul45.htm#_Toc162720341 | title=Flight to Vaharai | publisher=UTHR | accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref> Over the next few weeks an estimated 20,000 civilians fled from [[Vakarai]] to government-controlled areas, fearing the imminent assault. The army launched a new offensive in mid-January, and Vakarai fell to the advancing troops on 19 January. While the offensive in the East was ongoing, the LTTE and others accused the government of murdering 15 civilians in the [[Padahuthurai bombing]] on 2 January, when the air force bombed what they claimed to be an [[LTTE]] naval base in Illuppaikadavai in northern Sri Lanka.<ref name="trib1">{{cite news | url=http://www.asiantribune.com/index.php?q=node/3962 | title=Sri Lanka: Mystery shrouds over the killing of civilians in Mannar | work=[[Asian Tribune]] | date=3 January 2007 | accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slmm.lk/press_releases/statement%20-%20air%20strike.pdf|format=PDF|title=Press release on 29 April 2006 SUBJECT: Air strikes violate the Ceasefire Agreement|accessdate=2 March 2007|work=SLMM|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070625102927/http://www.slmm.lk/press_releases/statement%20-%20air%20strike.pdf|archivedate=25 June 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The loss of Vakarai had been predicted to cut off supply routes of the northern Tigers to their cadres in the east, thus weakening the Tigers' already diminishing grip on the east.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.asiantribune.com/index.php?q=node/4211|title=Tigers admit fall of Vakarai |work = Asian Tribune| date = 20 January 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url =http://www.asiantribune.com/index.php?q=node/4208|title =Sri Lanka Security forces captured LTTE controlled Vaharai|work = Asian Tribune| date = 19 January 2007}}</ref>

As the military offensive was ongoing, the LTTE continued to carry out attacks against civilians in government-held territory. On 1 April 2007 the military accused the LTTE of killing six Sinhalese tsunami aid workers in the eastern district of Batticaloa.<ref name="smh-4/2/07">{{cite news|title=Sri Lanka says rebels killed aid workers|date=2 April 2007|url =http://www.smh.com.au/news/World/Sri-Lanka-says-rebels-killed-aid-workers/2007/04/02/1175366108841.html|work =The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate =22 April 2007}}</ref><ref name="toi-4/2/07">{{cite news|title=Tamil Tigers kill 6 civilian workers in Lanka|date=2 April 2007|url =http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/NEWS/World/Rest_of_World/Tamil_Tigers_kill_6_civilian_workers_in_Lanka/articleshow/1842392.cms|work=The Times of India |accessdate =22 April 2007}}</ref> The next day suspected LTTE fighters set off a bomb aboard a civilian bus in Ampara, which killed 17 people, including three children.<ref name="bbc-4/2/07">{{cite news|title=Sri Lanka blast 'kills civilians'|date=2 April 2007|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/6517167.stm|publisher=BBC|accessdate =22 April 2007}}</ref><ref name="mod-bus-4/2/07">{{cite news|title =Seventeen persons killed, over two dozens injured- Ampara [4th Lead]|date =2 April 2007|url =http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20070402_07|work =Ministry of Defence|accessdate =22 April 2007|deadurl =yes|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20070407165748/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20070402_07|archivedate =7 April 2007|df =dmy-all}}</ref>

Troops mostly operating in small groups of Special Forces and Commando units began a new operation in February<ref name="ra-4/12/07" /> to clear the last remaining LTTE fighters from the Eastern Province. As part of the operation, troops captured the key LTTE base in [[Kokkadicholai]] on 28 March,<ref name="mod-kkd-28 March 2007">{{cite news|title=Kokkadicholai LTTE base falls to SL Army|date=28 March 2007|url=http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20070328_06|work=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=22 April 2007|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070403180143/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20070328_06|archivedate=3 April 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and the strategic [[A5 highway (Sri Lanka)|A5 highway]] on 12 April, bringing the entire highway under government control for the first time in 15 years.<ref name="mod-a5-4/12/07">{{cite news|title=SL Army Troops gain complete control over the A-5 Main Road|date=12 April 2007|url=http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20070411_07|work=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=22 April 2007|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927175656/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20070411_07|archivedate=27 September 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This meant the LTTE's presence in the east was reduced to a 140-square-kilometer pocket of jungle in the Thoppigala area northwest of Batticaloa.<ref name="ra-4/12/07">{{cite news|title=Sri Lanka captures key highway in rebel territory|date=12 April 2007|url=http://www.radioaustralia.net.au/news/stories/s1895901.htm|work =Radio Australia|accessdate =22 April 2007}}</ref> After the three-month-long [[Battle of Thoppigala]], the army captured the Thoppigala peak on 11 July 2007, ending the LTTE's military capability in the Eastern Province and concluding Eelam War IV in the Eastern theatre.<ref name="Baron's cap battle-2007-07-11">{{cite news | title=Sri Lanka declares fall of rebel east, Tigers defiant | agency=Reuters | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idUSCOL15933520070711 | accessdate=11 July 2007 | date=11 July 2007}}</ref>

==Government offensive in the North==
{{Main article|2008–2009 SLA Northern offensive}}

Sporadic fighting in the North had been going on for months, but the intensity of the clashes increased after September 2007. During clashes in the Forward Defence Lines, separating their forces, both sides exchanged heavy artillery fire, after which military incursions followed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7046629.stm|title=Sri Lanka on brink of all-out war|publisher=BBC News|date=16 October 2007|accessdate=31 December 2007|first=Ethirajan|last=Anbarasan}}</ref> By December 2007, the LTTE defences at Uyilankulama, Parappakandal and Thampanai were lost to advancing troops of the Sri Lanka Army.<ref name="mod-ma-22 December 2007">{{cite news|title =LTTE defences in Mannar and Vavuniya fall to army; terrorists on the run with soaring casualties|date =22 December 2007|url =http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20071222_08|work =Ministry of Defence|accessdate =31 December 2007|deadurl =yes|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20071225110603/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20071222_08|archivedate =25 December 2007|df =dmy-all}}</ref>

In an interview with the ''[[Sunday Observer]]'' the Army Commander Lt. Gen. Sarath Fonseka said that the Army had occupied the LTTE's Forward Defence Lines and surrounded the Wanni LTTE bases from all directions. He also said that there were around 3,000 Tigers remaining and that the military intended to annihilate them within the first six months of the next year.<ref name="mod-no-30 December 2007">{{cite news|title =Wanni is surrounded on all prongs|date =30 December 2007|url =http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20071230_05|work =Ministry of Defence|accessdate =31 December 2007|deadurl =yes|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20080101155601/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20071230_05|archivedate =1 January 2008|df =dmy-all}}</ref> A day later there were less optimistic statements by Army, Air Force and Navy Commanders. The Army was to face an estimated 5,000 Tiger cadres in the Wanni. The Commander of the Army intended to shift the current battles in the Forward Defence Lines to a decisive phase in August 2008. In the Commanders' view, it was quite possible to defeat the LTTE in 2008.<ref name="autogenerated2b">{{cite news |title= Forces' Chiefs predict Tiger extinction in 2008 |date= 31 December 2007 |url= http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20071231_01 |work= www.defence.lk |agency= Ministry of Defence |accessdate= 31 December 2007 |deadurl= yes |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080101155611/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20071231_01 |archivedate= 1 January 2008 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>

The [[military of Sri Lanka]] claimed that the leader of the LTTE, [[Velupillai Prabhakaran]], was seriously injured during air strikes carried out by the [[Sri Lanka Air Force]] on a bunker complex in Jayanthinagar on 26 November 2007.<ref name="mod-vp-19 December 2007">{{cite news|title=Prabhakaran injured in air attack|date=19 December 2007|url=http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20071219_05|work=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=26 December 2007|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071221192746/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20071219_05|archivedate=21 December 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Earlier, on 2 November 2007, [[S. P. Thamilselvan]], the head of the LTTE political wing, was killed during another government air raid.<ref>{{cite news|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7074450.stm|title = Senior Tamil Tiger leader killed|publisher=BBC News| date = 2 November 2007|accessdate =31 December 2007}}</ref> The Sri Lanka Air Force openly vowed to destroy the entire leadership of the LTTE.<ref name="autogenerated2b" /> On 5 January 2008, Colonel Charles, Head of LTTE Military Intelligence, was killed in a [[claymore mine]] ambush by a [[Long Range Reconnaissance Patrol (Sri Lanka)]] (LRRP).<ref>{{cite news|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7173679.stm|title = Tamil intelligence chief killed|publisher=BBC News| date = 6 January 2008|accessdate =6 January 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.tamilnet.com/art.html?catid=13&artid=24197|title = LTTE's Head of Military Intelligence killed in Claymore ambush|publisher = [[TamilNet]]| date = 6 January 2008|accessdate =6 January 2008}}</ref>

===Abrogation of ceasefire agreement===
Defense secretary [[Gotabhaya Rajapaksa]] urged the government to abandon the ceasefire agreement in December 2007,<ref name="Daily">{{cite news|url = http://www.dailynews.lk/2007/12/29/sec01.asp|title = Ban LTTE, end truce|work = Daily News|date = 29 December 2007|deadurl = yes|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071231054702/http://www.dailynews.lk/2007/12/29/sec01.asp|archivedate = 31 December 2007|df = dmy-all}}</ref> and on 2 January 2008, the Sri Lankan government officially did so.<ref name="afp">{{cite news|url=http://www.france24.com/france24Public/en/archives/news/world/20080102-sri-lanka-tamil-tiger-cease-fire-end.php |title=Government ends ceasefire with Tamil Tigers |agency=Agence France-Presse |date=2 January 2008 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205104725/http://www.france24.com/france24Public/en/archives/news/world/20080102-sri-lanka-tamil-tiger-cease-fire-end.php |archivedate=5 December 2008 }}</ref> Between February 2002 to May 2007, [[Sri Lanka Monitoring Mission]] had documented 3,830 ceasefire violations by the LTTE versus 351 by the security forces.<ref name="rep" /> From May 2007, the SLMM ceased making determinations on ceasefire violations. Thus the government stated there was no need for a ceasefire any more. Several donor countries expressed their disappointment at the Sri Lankan government's withdrawal.<ref name="Ministry">{{cite news|url= http://www.regjeringen.no/en/dep/ud/Press-Contacts/News/2008/Norway-regrets-the-Government-of-Sri-Lan.html?id=495581|title = Norway regrets the Government of Sri Lanka’s decision to terminate the 2002 ceasefire agreement| publisher = Ministry of Foreign Affairs|date = 2 January 2008}}</ref><ref name="Foreign">{{cite news|url = http://w01.international.gc.ca/MinPub/Publication.aspx?isRedirect=True&Language=E&publication_id=385729&docnumber=2|title = Statement on the possible escalation of violence in sri lanka|publisher = Foreign Affairs and International Trade Canada|date = 3 January 2008|deadurl = yes|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080107090421/http://w01.international.gc.ca/MinPub/Publication.aspx?isRedirect=True&Language=E&publication_id=385729&docnumber=2|archivedate = 7 January 2008|df = dmy-all}}</ref> The LTTE formally responded that since the government had unilaterally withdrawn from the ceasefire agreement without any justification and that they were prepared to continue to honour the agreement, the international community ought to immediately remove the bans it had placed on the LTTE.<ref name="bbc">{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7180761.stm|title = Tamil Tigers in ceasefire appeal|publisher=BBC |date = 10 January 2008|accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref><ref name="cfa">{{cite news|url= http://www.tamilnet.com/art.html?catid=13&artid=24249|title = LTTE requests Norway to continue facilitation, urges IC's support for Tamil rights|publisher = TamilNet |date = 10 January 2008}}</ref>

The government then attempted to open a third front along the [[Muhamalai Forward Defence Line]]. After an initial setback on 23 April,<ref name="apr2308">{{cite news|url= http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/asiapcf/04/23/srilanka.battle/index.html|title = Sources: Tigers' feint kills 100 Sri Lanka troops| publisher = CNN |date = 23 April 2008}}</ref> the Sri Lankan Army advanced rapidly, capturing the town of Adampan on 9 May,<ref name="mod-ma-05/09/08">{{cite news|title=Army captures Adampan Town – Mannar front|date=19 May 2008|url=http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20080509_02|work=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=11 May 2008|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080512112242/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20080509_02|archivedate=12 May 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Mannar "Rice Bowl" which consists of the island's most fertile paddy fields on 30 June,<ref name="bloomb">{{cite news|title=Sri Lanka Says Mannar `Rice Bowl' Seized From Rebels|date=30 June 2008|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=aqoAuFPYlVdA&refer=home|work=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]|accessdate=21 January 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130228154743/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=aqoAuFPYlVdA&refer=home|archivedate=28 February 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Vidattaltivu]] on 16 July,<ref name="mod-ma-16 July 2008">{{cite news|title =Vidattaltivu Liberated; terrorists suffer fatal blow|date =16 July 2008|url =http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20080716_03|work =Ministry of Defence|accessdate =16 July 2008|deadurl =yes|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20080718234304/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20080716_03|archivedate =18 July 2008|df =dmy-all}}</ref> and Iluppaikkadavai on 20 July.<ref name="mod-ma-20 July 2008">{{cite news|title =Troops Liberate Illuppaikkadavai|date =20 July 2008|url =http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20080720_02|work =Ministry of Defence|accessdate =20 July 2008|deadurl =yes|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20080722223609/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20080720_02|archivedate =22 July 2008|df =dmy-all}}</ref>

On 21 July 2008, the LTTE announced that it would be declaring a unilateral ceasefire from 28 July to 4 August, to coincide with the 15th summit of the heads of state of [[SAARC]] to be held in Colombo.<ref name="dm 22 July 2008">{{cite news|first=Jamila|last=Najmuddin|title=LTTE set to declare unilateral ceasefire|date=22 July 2008|work=Daily Mirror | url =http://www.dailymirror.wijeya.lk/DM_BLOG/Sections/frmNewsDetailView.aspx?ARTID=21107|accessdate =22 July 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080722223548/http://www.dailymirror.wijeya.lk/DM_BLOG/Sections/frmNewsDetailView.aspx?ARTID=21107 |archivedate = 22 July 2008}}</ref> However, the government of Sri Lanka dismissed the LTTE's offer as needless and treacherous.<ref name="mod-ma-25 July 2008">{{cite news|title=LTTE's ceasefire: Public relations or more? |date=25 July 2008 |url=http://in.rediff.com/news/2008/jul/25guest2.htm |work=Rediff News |accessdate=4 August 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080730064925/http://in.rediff.com/news/2008/jul/25guest2.htm |archivedate=30 July 2008 |deadurl=yes |df=dmy }}</ref>

===Significant military gains by the government===
On 2 August 2008, Vellankulam town, the LTTE's last stronghold in [[Mannar District]], fell to the advancing SLA troops, completing the eight-month effort to recapture the district.<ref name="mod-ma-08/02/08">{{cite news|title =Troops capture LTTE's last stronghold in Mannar District|date =2 August 2008|url =http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20080802_06|work =Ministry of Defence|accessdate =2 August 2008|deadurl =yes|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20080805155156/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20080802_06|archivedate =5 August 2008|df =dmy-all}}</ref>  The Army followed this up by taking control of [[Mallavi]] on 2 September, following weeks of heavy military confrontation.<ref name="mod-ma-09/02/08">{{cite news|title =LTTE's strategic bastion Mallavi falls to security forces|date =2 September 2008|url =http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20080902_07|work =Ministry of Defence|accessdate =2 September 2008|deadurl =yes|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20080906000010/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20080902_07|archivedate =6 September 2008|df =dmy-all}}</ref> The LTTE countered with a surprise attack on the [[Vavuniya]] air base on 9 September, in which both sides claimed victory.<ref name="mod-va-9 September 2008">{{cite news|title =Security Forces crush major terror attack at Vavuniya|date =9 September 2008|url =http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20080909_02|work =Ministry of Defence|accessdate =9 September 2008|deadurl =yes|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20080911203435/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20080909_02|archivedate =11 September 2008|df =dmy-all}}</ref><ref name="mod-tn-9 September 2008">{{cite news|title=Mission on Vanni SF HQ successful, Tiger aircrafts (sic) safe – LTTE|date=9 September 2008|url =http://www.tamilnet.com/art.html?catid=13&artid=26876|work =TamilNet|accessdate =10 September 2008}}</ref><ref name="mod-bbc-09/10/08">{{cite news|title=Sri Lanka jets attack rebel base|date=10 September 2008|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7607610.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate =10 September 2008}}</ref>

From Mannar, the Army had entered [[Kilinochchi District]], the last stronghold of the LTTE, at the end of July,<ref>{{cite web|author=Gamini Gunaratna, Sri Lanka News Paper by LankaPage.com (LLC)- Latest Hot News from Sri Lanka |url=http://www.colombopage.com/archive_08/August1145347CH.html |title=Sri Lankan troops enter Tigers’ final frontier |publisher=Colombopage.com |date=1 August 2008 |accessdate=17 May 2009}}</ref> with the intention of taking [[Kilinochchi]] before the end of the year. On 3 October 2008, a UN aid convoy managed to unload all its cargo in Kilinochchi District and described Kilinochchi town as having been nearly abandoned,<ref name="mod-bbc-10/03/08">{{cite news|title=Civilians flee Tamil Tiger centre|date=10 October 2008|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7651232.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate =3 October 2008|first=Swaminathan|last=Natarajan}}</ref> but the LTTE were able to kill retired Major General [[Janaka Perera]] along with 26 other victims in a suicide blast on 6 October.<ref name="mod-bbc-10/06/08">{{cite news|title = Suicide blast hits Sri Lanka town|date=6 October 2008|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7653945.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate =6 October 2008}}</ref>

On 17 October 2008, SLA troops cut off the [[A32 highway (Sri Lanka)|Mannar-Poonaryn A32 highway]] north of Nachchikuda, the main remaining [[Sea Tiger]] stronghold on the northwestern coast of the island, thus effectively encircling it.<ref name="mod-ki-17 October 2008">{{cite news|title =Troops encircle Nachchikudha; LTTE on the verge of losing Sea Tiger stronghold|date =17 October 2008|url =http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20081017_07|work =Ministry of Defence|accessdate =17 October 2008|deadurl =yes|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20081020031941/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20081017_07|archivedate =20 October 2008|df =dmy-all}}</ref> They began their assault on 28 October and captured it the next day.<ref name="mod-ki-28 October 2008">{{cite news|title =SLA crush LTTE defences: fall of Nachchikuda imminent|date =28 October 2008|url =http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20081028_08|work =Ministry of Defence|accessdate =28 October 2008|deadurl =yes|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20081031072110/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20081028_08|archivedate =31 October 2008|df =dmy-all}}</ref><ref name="mod-ki-29 October 2008">{{cite news|title =Nachchikuda falls to troops – Kilinochchi|date =29 October 2008|url =http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20081029_08|work =Ministry of Defence|accessdate =29 October 2008|deadurl =yes|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20081101061848/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20081029_08|archivedate =1 November 2008|df =dmy-all}}</ref> After that the Army Task Force 1 continued their advance towards Pooneryn and captured Kiranchchi, Palavi, Veravil, Valaipadu and Devil's Point.<ref name="mod-ki-11 November 2008">{{cite news|title =Heavy fighting at Wanni fronts; Troops recover 9 LTTE bodies|date =11 November 2008|url =http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20081111_11|work =Ministry of Defence|accessdate =11 November 2008|deadurl =yes|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20110510102849/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20081111_11|archivedate =10 May 2011|df =dmy-all}}</ref><ref name="mod-bbc-11 November 2008">{{cite news|title=Tamil Tiger 'strong point taken'|date=11 November 2008|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7722705.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate =12 November 2008}}</ref> On 15 November 2008, troops of the Army Task Force 1 entered the strategically important Tiger stronghold of [[Pooneryn]].<ref name="mod-bbc-15 November 2008">{{cite news|title=Sri Lanka army 'takes Tiger base'|date=15 November 2008|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7730850.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate =15 November 2008|first=Roland|last=Buerk}}</ref><ref name="mod-ki-15 November 2008">{{cite news |title=Mop up operations in progress in Pooneryn salient; Air Force comes to troops assistance |date=15 November 2008 |url=http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20081115_04 |work=Ministry of Defence |accessdate=16 November 2008 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201171559/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20081115_04 |archivedate=1 December 2008 |df=dmy }}</ref> Simultaneously, the newly created Army Task Force 3 was introduced into the area of [[Maankulam (Sri Lanka)|Mankulam]] with the objective of engaging the LTTE cadres in a new battlefront towards the east of the [[A9 highway (Sri Lanka)|Jaffna–Kandy A9 highway]].<ref name="mod-mu-11/03/08">{{cite news|title =Army Task Force 3 comes into action; pounds LTTE positions in Mankulam|date =3 November 2008|url =http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20081103_05|work =Ministry of Defence|accessdate =3 November 2008|deadurl =yes|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20081106110927/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20081103_05|archivedate =6 November 2008|df =dmy-all}}</ref> SLA troops captured [[Maankulam (Sri Lanka)|Mankulam]] and the surrounding area on 17 November 2008.<ref name="mod-mu-17 November 2008">{{cite news|title=Troops overrun Mankulama: LTTE flee amidst heavy casualties- Mullaittivu|date=17 November 2008|url=http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20081117_06|work=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=22 November 2008|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110510103335/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20081117_06|archivedate=10 May 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

Meanwhile, the situation of more than 200,000 civilians who had been displaced in the latest round of fighting was turning into a humanitarian disaster; however, due to a number of reasons including doubts regarding the sincerity of the LTTE's negotiations, neither Western governments nor India intervened to broker a new ceasefire.<ref name="mod-bbc-10/17/08-2">{{cite news|title=West urged not to ignore Sri Lanka|date=17 October 2008|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7676839.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate =18 October 2008|first=Ethirajan|last=Anbarasan}}</ref>

===Fall of Kilinochchi and subsequent events===
{{Main article|Battle of Kilinochchi (2008–2009)}}

The Sri Lankan Army began the attack on Kilinochchi on 23 November 2008. Troops were attacking rebels' defences from three directions.<ref name="mod-bbc-24 November 2008">{{cite news|title=S Lanka attack on rebel 'capital'|date=24 November 2008|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7745162.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate =24 November 2008}}</ref> However, the LTTE offered a stiff resistance, and the prolonged attack resulted in heavy casualties on both sides.<ref name="mod-bbc-17 December 2008">{{cite news|title='Many dead' in Sri Lanka battles|date=17 December 2008|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7786183.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate =26 December 2008}}</ref>
[[File:Tractors. Jan 2009 displacement in the Vanni.jpg|thumb|260px|Civilians being displaced as a result of the Sri Lanka Army's military offensive. January 2009.]]

Not until 1 January 2009 were SLA troops able to capture [[Paranthan]], located to the north of Kilinochchi along the A-9 route. This isolated the southern periphery of the [[Elephant Pass]] LTTE foothold and also exposed the LTTE's main fortification at Kilinochchi.<ref name="mod-ki-1 January 2009">{{cite news|title =Paranthan LTTE garrison captured: Troops make headway at Wanni battles|date =1 January 2009|url =http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20090101_01|work =Ministry of Defence|accessdate =6 January 2009|deadurl =yes|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20110510103220/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20090101_01|archivedate =10 May 2011|df =dmy-all}}</ref> This made the capture of Kilinochchi, which the rebels had used for over a decade as their de facto administrative capital, far simpler, and they were able to accomplish this on 2 January. The loss of Killinochchi caused a substantial dent in the LTTE's image as a capable, ruthless terrorist group,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2009-01/03/content_10596928.htm |title=The fall of rebel headquarters: what does it hold for Sri Lanka? |agency=Xinhua News Agency |date=3 January 2009 |accessdate=17 May 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090604103501/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2009-01/03/content_10596928.htm |archivedate=4 June 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and observers forecast the LTTE was likely to collapse before long under unbearable military pressure on multiple fronts.<ref>[http://www.island.lk/2009/01/03/editorial.html A blow to global terror].</ref>

The Tigers quickly abandoned their positions on the Jaffna peninsula to make a last stand in the jungles of [[Mullaitivu]], their last main base.<ref name="mod-bbc-01/08/09">{{cite news|title=Army 'takes more Tiger territory'|date=8 January 2009|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7817110.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate =8 January 2009}}</ref> The entire Jaffna peninsula was captured by the Sri Lanka Army by 14 January 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601091&sid=aehebYR1I8gI&refer=india |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120721035858/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601091&sid=aehebYR1I8gI&refer=india |dead-url=yes |archive-date=21 July 2012 |title=Sri Lankan Military Seizes Last Rebel Base on Jaffna Peninsula |publisher=Bloomberg |date=14 January 2009 |accessdate=17 May 2009 }}</ref> However, they were unable to hold out for long, and on 25 January, SLA troops captured Mullaitivu.<ref name="mod-bbc-25 January 2009">{{cite news|title=Last Tamil Tiger bastion 'taken'|date=25 January 2009|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7849684.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate =25 January 2009}}</ref><ref name="nytimes 2009/01/26">{{cite news|author = Somini Sepgupta |title = Sri Lankan Troops Take Last Rebel Stronghold |date = 26 January 2009 |work=The New York Times |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/26/world/asia/26lanka.html?hp |accessdate =26 January 2009}}</ref> The last Sea Tiger base in Chalai was next to fall on 5 February, reducing the territory under rebel control to less than some 200&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>.<ref name="mod-mu-02/05/09">{{cite news|title =Army captures last sea tiger base & clears entire Visuamadu area|date =5 February 2009|url =http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20090205_08|work =Ministry of Defence|accessdate =5 February 2009|deadurl =yes|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20090227182635/http://defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20090205_08|archivedate =27 February 2009|df =dmy-all}}</ref>

This stage of the war was marked by increased brutality against civilians and rapidly mounting civilian casualties. On 19 February 2009, [[Human Rights Watch]] issued a report accusing the Sri Lankan army of "slaughtering" the civilians during indiscriminate artillery attacks (including repeated shelling of hospitals) and calling on the Sri Lankan government to end its policy of "detaining displaced persons" in military-controlled internment camps. Human Rights Watch also urged the Tamil Tigers to permit trapped civilians to leave the war zone and to "stop shooting at those who try to flee".<ref name="hrw-19 February 2008">[https://www.hrw.org/sites/default/files/reports/srilanka0209webwcover_0.pdf War on the Displaced: Sri Lankan Army and LTTE Abuses against Civilians in the Vanni], Human Rights Watch. 19 February 2009.</ref> The UN was also concerned over the condition of internally displaced persons and estimated that some 200,000 people were being squeezed into a narrow 14&nbsp;square kilometre patch of land on the coast in Vanni, which the government had declared the 'no-fire zone'.<ref name="un-27 February 2008">[https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=30046&Cr=sri+lanka&Cr1= War UN relief chief concerned over physical condition of Sri Lankans trapped by clashes], United Nations. 27 February 2009.</ref>

On 20 February 2009, two LTTE planes on [[2009 suicide air raid on Colombo|a suicide mission]] carried out a [[kamikaze]] style air attack on the Sri Lankan capital [[Colombo]], killing 2 and wounding 45, but both planes were shot down by the [[Sri Lankan Air Force]] before they could damage the intended targets which were the Army Headquarters and the main Air Force base.<ref name="australian-nottamed">{{cite news | work = The Australian | title = Kamikaze raid shows the Tamil Tigers have not been tamed | url = http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,25091354-25837,00.html | date = 22 September 2009 | accessdate = 23 February 2009 | first = Amanda | last = Hodge | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090508100212/http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,25091354-25837,00.html | archive-date = 8 May 2009 | dead-url = yes | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Tamil Tiger planes raid Colombo|date=20 February 2009|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7902392.stm|publisher=BBC|accessdate =20 February 2009}}</ref> By late March, the Tamil Tigers controlled only one square kilometre outside the no-fire zone, down from about 15,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> a mere three years ago. Political pressure was placed on President Rajapaksa to find a political solution to the conflict and he called for a meeting with [[Tamil National Alliance]], but they refused until the government resolved the humanitarian crisis faced by civilians trapped in the fighting.

The [[Battle of Aanandapuram]], which was described by military analyst/journalist [[D. B. S. Jeyaraj]] as the "defining moment" of the 3 decade war, was fought on 5 April. This battle saw the demise of most of the battle-hardened ground commanders of the LTTE, including Velayuthapillai Baheerathakumar ''alias'' Theepan, the overall commander of the LTTE northern front fighting formations. SLA soldiers numbering more than 50,000 from 5 divisions participated in the battle encircling the LTTE cadres inside a small littoral strip of territory located between the [[A35 highway (Sri Lanka)|Paranthan-Mullaitivu A35 highway]], [[Nanthi Lagoon|Nanthikadal]] and [[Chalai Lagoon]]s on one side and the Indian Ocean on the other. Rebel casualties amounted to 625.<ref>{{cite news|title=Anatomy of the LTTE military debacle at Aanandapuram|date=10 April 2009|url=http://dbsjeyaraj.com/dbsj/archives/315|work=[[D. B. S. Jeyaraj]]|accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref>

===Fighting in the 'No-Fire Zone'===
SLA troops were able to push the Tamil Tigers into the no-fire zone set up for civilians.<ref name="mod-mu-04/05/09">{{cite news|title=Troops unshackle LTTE grip on Puthukkudiyirippu: Over 250 terrorists killed|date=5 April 2009|url=http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20090405_04|work=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=5 April 2009|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090408124001/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20090405_04|archivedate=8 April 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Army 'routs Tigers in north-east'|date=5 April 2009|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7984184.stm|publisher=BBC|accessdate =5 April 2009|first=Anbarasan|last=Ethirajan}}</ref> The LTTE then built a {{Convert|3|km|adj=on|0}} long [[bunding|bund]] in the no-fire zone, trapping over 30,000 civilians, but the SLA was able to destroy this.<ref name="mod-mu-20 April 2009">{{cite news|title=World's largest hostage rescue mission becomes success; over 30,000 rescued|date=20 April 2009|url=http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20090420_09|work=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=20 April 2009|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120923171711/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20090420_09|archivedate=23 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Thousands flee Sri Lanka combat|date=20 April 2009|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8007465.stm|publisher=BBC|accessdate =20 April 2009}}</ref>

On 21 April, Sri Lankan troops launched an assault, targeting LTTE leader, [[Vellupillai Prabhakaran]]. At the same time, a mass Tamil exodus from the 'no-fire zone' was underway.<ref>{{cite news|title=Final assault begins as LTTE vows to fight on|date=22 April 2009|url = http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/Final-assault-begins-as-LTTE-vows-to-fight-on/articleshow/4432129.cms|work=The Times of India |accessdate =22 April 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Mass Tamil exodus from rebel area|date=21 April 2009|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8010818.stm|publisher=BBC|accessdate =22 April 2009}}</ref> The next day, two senior LTTE members (LTTE media co-ordinator Velayuthan Thayanithi, ''alias'' Daya Master, and a top interpreter Kumar Pancharathnam, ''alias'' George)<ref>[http://defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20090422_07 Daya Master and George seek refuge with Army] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090426230549/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20090422_07 |date=26 April 2009 }}.</ref> surrendered to the advancing Sri Lankan army. This came as "a rude shock" and a major setback for the rebel leadership.<ref>{{cite news|title=Two key Tamil Tigers 'surrender'| date=22 April 2009|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8012016.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate =24 April 2009}}</ref> When asked why they had surrendered, both men stressed that rebels were shooting at the civilians and preventing them from escaping from the 'no-fire zone' to safety in government-controlled areas. They also alleged that the LTTE were still abducting and conscripting children as young as 14 years old, and would fire at anyone who tried to resist.<ref>{{cite news|last=Natarajan |first=Swaminathan |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/7985155.stm |title=World &#124; Sri Lanka civilians tell of war ordeal |publisher=BBC News |date=6 April 2009 |accessdate=17 May 2009}}</ref><ref>[http://defence.lk/new.asp?fname=HiddenReality Hidden Reality] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090502080311/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=HiddenReality |date=2 May 2009 }}, interview with Daya Master and George</ref>

By 25 April, the area under the LTTE was reduced to 10&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>. While the Tamil exodus from the 'no-fire zone' continued, the UN estimated that around 6,500 civilians may have been killed and another 14,000 wounded between January 2009 and April 2009.<ref>{{cite news|title=Prabhakaran trapped in 10sqkm [sic] area:Lanka army| date=24 April 2009|url = http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/World/Prabhakaran-trapped-in-10sqkm-areaLanka-army/articleshow/4445465.cms|work=The Times of India | accessdate =24 April 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sri Lanka rejects rebel ceasefire| date=27 April 2009|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8019865.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate =12 May 2009}}</ref> The BBC reported that the land recaptured by the army from the rebels was totally depopulated and utterly devastated.<ref>{{cite news|title=Journey to Sri Lanka's frontline| date=25 April 2009|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8017945.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate =11 May 2009|first=Charles|last=Haviland}}</ref>

As fighting continued, a group of independent United Nations experts called on the [[Human Rights Council]] to urgently set up an international inquiry to address the "critical" situation in Sri Lanka amid fighting between the Army and Tamil rebels. According to the [[UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs]] ([[OCHA]]), over 196,000 people fled the conflict zone, a shrinking pocket of land on the north-east coastline, where clashes continued between government troops and the LTTE, while at least 50,000 people were still trapped there.<ref>{{cite news|title=Urgent international scrutiny needed in Sri Lanka, say UN rights experts|date=8 May 2009|url = https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=30740&Cr=Sri%20Lanka&Cr1=|publisher=United Nations|accessdate =11 May 2009}}</ref> A UN spokesman in Colombo, Gordon Weiss, said more than 100 children died during the "large-scale killing of civilians" and described the situation in northern Sri Lanka as a "bloodbath".<ref>{{cite news|title=UN mourns Sri Lanka 'bloodbath'|date=11 May 2009|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8043169.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate =11 May 2009}}</ref> UN Secretary-General [[Ban Ki-moon]] said he was appalled at the killing of hundreds of Sri Lankan civilians caught in the middle of hostilities between the army and separatist Tamil rebels over the weekend. He voiced deep concern over the continued use of heavy weapons in the conflict zone, but also stressed that the "reckless disrespect shown by the LTTE for the safety of civilians has led to thousands of people remaining trapped in the area".<ref>{{cite news|title=UN chief ‘appalled’ by weekend death toll in Sri Lankan conflict|date=11 May 2009|url = https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=30759&Cr=sri+lanka&Cr1=|publisher=United Nations|accessdate =12 May 2009}}</ref>

On 16 May 2009, Sri Lankan troops broke through LTTE defences and captured the last section of coastline held by Tamil Tiger rebels. The army reported it was set to "clear" remaining rebel-held land within days.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sri Lanka army 'controls coast'|date=16 May 2009|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8053091.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate =16 May 2009}}</ref><ref name="mod-mu-16 May 2009">{{cite news|title=Sri Lanka's coast free of terror; Army 58 Div links up with the 59 Div|date=16 May 2009|url=http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20090516_02|work=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=16 May 2009|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519180146/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20090516_02|archivedate=19 May 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Later the military claimed, allegedly citing intercepted LTTE communication, that rebels were preparing for a [[mass suicide]] after being effectively cut off from escape routes.<ref name="mod-nfz-16 May 2009">{{cite news|title=LTTE prepares for mass suicide; key terror leaders trapped|date=16 May 2009|url=http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20090516_08|work=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=16 May 2009|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519180152/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20090516_08|archivedate=19 May 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Some rebels were reported to have blown themselves up.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/may/17/tamil-tigers-surrender|title=Tamil Tigers announce plan to surrender|last=Chamberlain|first=Gethin|author2=David Batthy |date=17 May 2009|work=The Observer |accessdate=17 May 2009|location=London}}</ref>

==End of the war==

===16 May: Sri Lanka declares victory===
Addressing the [[Group of Eleven|G11]] summit in Jordan, [[President of Sri Lanka|President]] [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]] stated "my government, with the total commitment of our armed forces, has in an unprecedented humanitarian operation finally defeated the LTTE militarily".<ref name="voas">{{cite web|url=http://www.voanews.com/english/news/a-13-2009-05-16-voa15-68734572.html |title=Sri Lankan President Declares Military Defeat of Rebels |publisher=[[Voice of America]] |date=16 May 2009 |accessdate=18 August 2011}}</ref> Sri Lankan [[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Army]] [[Sarath Fonseka]] also declared victory over LTTE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2011/01/17/110117fa_fact_anderson |title=Death of the Tiger |work=The New Yorker |date=17 January 2011 |accessdate=18 August 2011}}</ref> Sri Lankan troops raced to clear the last LTTE pockets of resistance. As the last LTTE strongpoints crumbled, Sri Lankan troops killed 70 rebels attempting to escape by boat.<ref name="tonline">{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article6303682.ece |title=Sri Lankan troops 'kill' 70 escaping Tamil Tigers |work=The Times  |date=17 May 2009 |accessdate=18 August 2011 |location=London |first=Martin |last=Fletcher}}</ref> The whereabouts of LTTE leader [[Vellupillai Prabhakaran]] and other major rebel leaders were not certain.

===17 May: Tigers admit defeat===
The LTTE finally admitted defeat on 17 May 2009, with the rebels' chief of international relations, [[Selvarasa Pathmanathan]], stating on the website that "This battle has reached its bitter end ... We have decided to silence our guns. Our only regrets are for the lives lost and that we could not hold out for longer".<ref name="tonline1">{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article6305401.ece |title=Tamil Tigers admit defeat after battle reaches 'bitter end' |work=The Times  |date=18 May 2009 |accessdate=18 August 2011 |location=London |first1=Robert |last1=Bosleigh |first2=Jeremy |last2=Page}}</ref><ref name="correspondentscivil" />

===18 May: First claim of Prabhakaran's death===
The Sri Lankan armed forces claimed that the leader of the LTTE, [[Velupillai Prabhakaran]], was killed in the morning of 18 May 2009 while he was trying to flee the conflict zone in an ambulance. The announcement on state television came shortly after the military said it had surrounded Prabhakaran in a tiny patch of jungle in the north-east. ''The Daily Telegraph'' wrote that, according to Sri Lankan TV, Prabhakaran was "...&nbsp;killed in a rocket-propelled grenade attack as he tried to escape the war zone in an Ambulance with his closest aides. [[Colonel Soosai]], the leader of his "[[Sea Tigers]]" navy, and [[Pottu Amman (Tamil militant)|Pottu Amman]], his intelligence chief were also killed in the attack."<ref>{{cite news|last=Nelson |first=Dean |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/srilanka/5343129/Sri-Lanka-Tamil-Tiger-leader-Velupillai-Prabhakaran-and-his-lieutenants-eliminated.html |title=Sri Lanka: Tamil Tiger leader Velupillai Prabhakaran and his lieutenants 'eliminated' |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=18 May 2009 |accessdate=30 May 2009|location=London}}</ref>

The head of the Sri Lankan army, General [[Sarath Fonseka]], said the military had defeated the rebels and "liberated the entire country". Military spokesman [[Brigadier]] [[Udaya Nanayakkara]] stated 250 Tamil Tigers, who were hiding and fighting from within the no fire zone,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2009/05/17/sec04.asp |title=Security Sundayobserver.lk – Sri Lanka |publisher=Sundayobserver.lk |date=17 May 2009 |accessdate=30 May 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090521095500/http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2009/05/17/sec04.asp |archivedate=21 May 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> were killed overnight.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/in_depth/8055015.stm |title=South Asia &#124; Sri Lanka's rebel leader 'killed' |publisher=BBC News |date=19 May 2009 |accessdate=30 May 2009}}</ref>

===19 May: President addresses the Parliament and Prabhakaran is dead===
At 9:00&nbsp;am on 19 May 2009 [[President of Sri Lanka|President]] [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]] delivered a victory address to the [[Parliament of Sri Lanka|Parliament]] and declared that Sri Lanka is liberated from terrorism.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1183961/Sri-Lankan-TV-broadcasts-video-body-Tamil-Tiger-leader-President-declares-country-liberated-terrorism.html |title=Sri Lankan TV broadcasts 'video of body of Tamil Tiger leader' as President declares the country liberated from terrorism |work=Daily Mail  |date=20 May 2009 |accessdate=18 August 2011 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/may/18/tamil-tigers-killed-sri-lanka |title=Sri Lanka declares end to war with Tamil Tigers |work=The Guardian  |date=19 May 2009 |accessdate=18 August 2011|location=London |first1=Matthew |last1=Weaver |first2=Gethin |last2=Chamberlain}}</ref> Around 9:30&nbsp;am troops attached to Task Force VIII of [[Sri Lanka Army]], reported to its commander, [[Colonel]] G.V. Ravipriya that a body similar to Velupillai Prabhakaran has been found among the mangroves in Nandikadal lagoon.<ref name="lankaw">{{Cite news
|url=http://www.lankaweb.com/news/items/2011/06/11/no-peace-offer-from-prabhakaran-%E2%80%93-only-war/
|title=No peace offer from Prabhakaran – only war
|date=11 June 2011
|accessdate=20 June 2011
| work=Lanka Web
}}</ref> It was identified by the officer. At 12:15&nbsp;pm Army Commander [[Sarath Fonseka]] officially announced Prabhakaran's death, through the State television [[Independent Television Network|ITN]]. At around 1:00&nbsp;pm his body was shown in [[Swarnavahini]] for the first time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.army.lk/vgallery.php?galid=29 |title=Sri Lanka Army – Defenders of the Nation |publisher=Army.lk |accessdate=19 May 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090523092610/http://www.army.lk/vgallery.php?galid=29 |archivedate=23 May 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Prabakaran's identity was confirmed by [[Vinayagamoorthy Muralitharan|Karuna Amman]], his former confidant, and through DNA testing against his son's genetic material who had been killed earlier by the Sri Lanka Military.<ref name="DNA">{{Cite news
