{{short description|15th-century Ottoman historian}} {{Ottoman Turkish name|Tursun|Bey}} {{Infobox Muslim scholar |era = [[Ottoman Empire]] |image = |caption = |name = Tursun Beg |title= ''' Tursun Beg''' |birth_date = c. 1420 |death_date = |Maddhab = |school_tradition= |ethnicity = |region = |main_interests = Ottoman history |notable_ideas= |works = "Tarih-i Ebülfeth" ("The History of the Conqueror") | influences = | influenced = }}
'''Tursun Beg''' ({{lang-tr|Tursun Bey}}; probably born in mid-1420s in Bursa)<ref name="Encyclo Islam">Woodhead, Christine. "Ṭūrsūn Beg." Encyclopaedia of Islam, Second Edition. Brill, 2011.</ref> was an [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] bureaucrat and historian who wrote a chronicle dedicated to [[Mehmed the Conqueror|Mehmed II]].
==Life and career== Tursun Beg's life is only known from references in his chronicle. He came from a prominent [[timariot]] family and held a [[timar]] himself.<ref name="Encyclo Islam" /> He worked in the imperial [[divan]] and accompanied [[Mehmed II]] during the [[siege of Constantinople]] in 1453 that led to the [[fall of Constantinople]].<ref name="Encyclo Islam" />
==Works== Tursun Beg's only known work is the ''Tarih-i Ebülfeth'' (تاريخ ابو الفتح in Ottoman; "The History of the Conqueror").
==Bibliography== *Tursun Beg. ''The history of Mehmed the Conqueror''. [Tarih-i Ebülfeth] Halil Inalcik and Rhoads Murphey trans. Minneapolis: Bibliotheca Islamica, 1978. *Woodhead, Christine. "Tursun Beg." [[Encyclopaedia of Islam]]. 2nd Edition.
